**Russia Counterattacks Under Kursk, Ukraine's Operation May Be Decisive**
Western analysts believe that the next few months will be crucial. Experts think that the Ukrainian forces are unlikely to want to hold all the territories they have captured. Since August 2024, Ukraine has been conducting active offensive operations in the direction of Kursk, using not only national forces but also equipment provided by Western partners, particularly the UK. This includes the use of Challenger 2 tanks, which has caused a significant reaction from Russia. However, analysts believe that the threat of nuclear escalation, often emphasized by the Kremlin, is currently exaggerated. According to The Times, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky has suggested that the invasion was intended to facilitate future peace negotiations on Ukrainian terms, but no one thinks that negotiations are possible before spring and, likely, not before autumn 2025. Political commentator Tim Shipman notes, 'So what did Zelensky think? The answer is partly political, partly military.' Michael Clarke, a leading British defense analyst, stated that 'this is a classic military counterattack that tries to ease pressure in other places,' particularly on the Donbas. However, if Kyiv hoped that Moscow would immediately withdraw its troops from Ukraine to regain the Kursk foothold, Russian generals seem to have instead used the absence of four top Ukrainian regiments to advance in the Pokrovsk and Chasov Yar areas, according to the British publication. Military experts believe that the next few months may be decisive. According to analysts, Russia is preparing a counterattack under Kursk, which may begin by the end of October, before winter. Specialists agree that the Ukrainians will not want to try to hold all the captured positions. The Ukrainian operation in the Kursk region is currently a success for Zelensky and a shame for Russian military, writes The Times. Russia has already lost over 15,000 units of armored vehicles and 6,000 tanks, and is forced to use outdated models, such as the T-54, which were scrapped over 40 years ago. Western analysts agree that the success or failure of the Ukrainian operation under Kursk may significantly affect the further course of the war. At the same time, the unity of Western countries in supporting Ukraine remains important, which will be a key factor in countering Russian aggression. Tim Shipman notes that the only British weapon that has not yet been used on Russian territory is also the most powerful - the Storm Shadow. Since this cruise missile is a joint project, its use also requires the consent of the US and France (where the missiles are called Scalp), which fear escalation in relations with Russia. As President Vladimir Zelensky stated on August 17, the operation in the Kursk region is continuing as planned by Ukraine.
