**Ukrainian Forces in Kursk Region: A Challenge to Russian Army's Plans**
Roman Kostenko, the Secretary of the parliamentary committee on national security, defense, and intelligence, expressed doubts that the Russian army will be able to expel Ukrainian forces from the Kursk region by October 1. 'If we continue to operate at the same pace and intensity, and we are doing it seriously, building up positions to the west and east, it will be difficult for Putin to do this... We have combat units with combat experience, while Putin has units he has brought from different directions just to stop us. Now he needs to withdraw combat units that can counter ours and throw them into battle,' Kostenko said at a briefing on Wednesday. According to him, much will depend on the Ukrainian Armed Forces. 'If we can inflict such losses on them that they cannot continue to advance, they will undoubtedly have to bring in reserves,' Kostenko noted, emphasizing that such reserves can be brought in from the zone of active combat operations (east and south). The people's deputy noted that the Ukrainian operation in the Kursk region of the Russian Federation affects the entire theater of operations. 'In the Kursk operation, there were several tasks, some of which were completed, some not. But one of them was to force the enemy to redeploy their troops. And what do we see? The enemy is indeed redeploying some of their troops. We know about the 200th brigade from the Kramatorsk direction, we know about the 80th from the Dnipro direction... They are starting to redeploy, but they have a fundamental position - not to withdraw troops from the Pokrovsk direction. This is a strategic direction for them. And now we see that, even understanding that they do not have reserves to retake Kursk, and we continue to advance, they still bet on the territory of Donetsk,' Kostenko said.
